Build Identifier: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 6.1; en-GB; rv:1.9.2.13) Gecko/20101203 Firefox/3.6.13

During AJAX call,

XMLHttpRequest object getting duplicated.

Works well with all other browsers( chrome,safari)

Reproducible: Always

Steps to Reproduce:
1. Go to http://www.w3schools.com/ajax/tryit.asp?filename=tryajax_first
2. Chang the content as follows,for better transparency
<html>
<head>
<script type="text/javascript">
var Change_count=0;
function loadXMLDoc()
{
var xmlhttp;
if (window.XMLHttpRequest)
  {// code for IE7+, Firefox, Chrome, Opera, Safari
  xmlhttp=new XMLHttpRequest();
  }
else
  {// code for IE6, IE5
  xmlhttp=new ActiveXObject("Microsoft.XMLHTTP");
  }
xmlhttp.onreadystatechange=function()
  {
  Change_count++;
  alert('readyState-'+xmlhttp.readyState+',Cnt-'+Change_count);
  if (xmlhttp.readyState==4 )
    {
      if(xmlhttp.status==200)
      {
        alert('Status-'+xmlhttp.status);
        document.getElementById("myDiv").innerHTML=xmlhttp.responseText;
      }
    }
  }
xmlhttp.open("GET","ajax_info.txt",true);
xmlhttp.send();
}
</script>
</head>
<body>

<div id="myDiv"><h2>Let AJAX change this text</h2></div>
<button type="button" onclick="loadXMLDoc()">Change Content</button>

</body>
</html>

3.Click on "Edit and Click Me" at the top
4.Click on "Change Content" on right Frame
Actual Results:  
Ready State transistion from (1 to 4) occurs twice

Expected Results:  
Ready State transistion from (1 to 4) expected once

Checked this with latest Firefox 4.0 beta 7 , Same is the status

